<div id="c11">
<p>You might be interested in E. C. R. Hehner&#8217;s version of the proof; see his paper <a href="http://www.cs.toronto.edu/~hehner/God.pdf" rel="nofollow">Beautifying Godel</a> for details.</p>

<p>The distinction between program and data, the use of the character string data type, the use of an interpreter, and counting from zero allow the proof to be reduced to three lines.</p>

<p class="posted">posted by Alan
 on February 15, 2007 <a href="godel#c11" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>
<div id="c12">
<p>I second Brian&#8217;s recommendation to skip GEB. It&#8217;s very cleverly written, but the insights it offers are few. For example: the author dedicates a sonnet to Russel&#8217;s paradox when a sentence would suffice. It&#8217;s also guilty of jumping to the &#8220;exciting&#8221; popular science subjects - AI, DNA, robots, etc. - while providing little background or depth.</p>

<p class="posted">posted by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://watermargincoop.org"></a>
 on February 16, 2007 <a href="godel#c12" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
