<div id="c14">
<p>Actually, I&#8217;d advise you to try reading the original paper, which you can find here: http://www.research.ibm.com/people/h/hirzel/papers/canon00-goedel.pdf (and there are other translations too, some of them using either the original or a newer logic notation); try googling for &#8220;on formally undecidable&#8221; and Gödel.</p>

<p>It&#8217;s very interesting to read the proof itself, instead of the usual human-translation.</p>

<p class="posted">posted by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.hernan.moraldo.com.ar">Hernan Moraldo</a>
 on February 24, 2007 <a href="godel#c14" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
</div>
<div id="c17">
<p>GEB is very lucid if extremely long-winded and tangential.  I had a great time reading it as a teenager.  I don&#8217;t know if I&#8217;d have the patience for it now.  But it presents Gödel&#8217;s proof in a way that&#8217;s both complete (no serious technical gaps) and quite accessible to non-math people.  I later took the standard intro-to-mathematical-logic class (Math 125A at Berkeley) whose main result is Gödel&#8217;s proof, and found I already understood the subject pretty well just from having read GEB.  However, if you want a more serious (but still accessible) treatment from a standard math book, Herbert Enderton&#8217;s &#8220;Introduction to Mathematical Logic&#8221; is quite good.  It treats proof theory, model theory, and I think discusses axiomatic set theory to some extent, though he has a separate book for that.  Really, everyone should know a bit about this stuff.</p>

<p>Wikipedia&#8217;s coverage of these subjects is also quite good.  I guess I&#8217;d start with [[Mathematical logic]] and follow the links from there.</p>

<p class="posted">posted by Paul
 on March  1, 2007 <a href="godel#c17" rel="bookmark">#</a></p>
